```
shopsmart/
├── .github/
│   └── workflows/
│       └── build.yml    ← NEW: CI workflow file
├── client/
├── server/
└── ...
```

---

## How It Works

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    A[Developer pushes code] --> B[GitHub detects push/PR]
    B --> C[Triggers build.yml workflow]
    C --> D[Checkout code]
    D --> E[Setup Node.js 20]
    E --> F[npm install]
    F --> G[npm run build]
    G --> H[npm test]
    H --> I{Build Success?}
    I -->|Yes| J[✅ Green checkmark]
    I -->|No| K[❌ Build fails - blocks merge]
```

---

## Verification Plan

### Automated Verification
After creating the workflow file:

1. **Push to GitHub** - The workflow will automatically trigger
2. **Check Actions tab** - Go to your repo → Actions → See workflow run
3. **Verify green checkmark** - Both jobs should pass

### Manual Verification Steps

1. **Create a test branch and push:**
   ```bash
   cd /Users/prashant/shopsmart
   git checkout -b test-ci-pipeline
   git add .github/workflows/build.yml
   git commit -m "Add CI build verification workflow"
   git push origin test-ci-pipeline
   ```

2. **Open GitHub repository** → Go to **Actions** tab

3. **Verify the workflow appears** and starts running

4. **Check both jobs pass:**
   - `build-client` ✅
   - `build-server` ✅

5. **Create a Pull Request** to verify PR triggers work

---

## Benefits

| Benefit | Description |
|---------|-------------|
| **Consistency** | Same check for everyone, every time |
| **Early Detection** | Catches broken builds immediately |
| **No "Works on My Machine"** | Runs in clean Ubuntu environment |
| **PR Blocking** | Can be set to block merges if build fails |
| **Visibility** | Everyone sees build status on GitHub |
